    "Related Work": "Existing work primarily focuses on static layer skipping or thresholding mechanisms that do not adapt to the changing input distributions during inference. For instance, methods like Spectral Quantization Routing and Geometric Interference Cancellation propose static approaches to manage computational complexity and robustness. In contrast, this proposal introduces a dynamic, real-time mechanism that adjusts layer engagement on-the-fly, utilizing a PAC-Bayes framework to ensure generalization and stability.",
    "Abstract": "We propose a novel method called Dynamic Layer Skipping (DLS) that leverages real-time activation covariance metrics to manage layer engagement dynamically in neural networks. Traditional inference strategies often struggle with strict latency constraints, particularly in latency-critical applications. DLS computes the covariance of activations at each layer and establishes a threshold for engagement based on the spectral properties of these activations. When the covariance indicates low uncertainty or robustness, the method permits skipping certain layers during inference, thereby optimizing throughput without sacrificing accuracy. This dynamic mechanism is grounded in PAC-Bayes principles, ensuring generalization stability despite layer skipping. We will empirically validate DLS across several benchmarks, measuring its performance against static layer engagement strategies in terms of accuracy, latency, and computational efficiency. By providing a mathematically rigorous framework for layer engagement, our approach offers a scalable solution for real-time applications.",
