### Reflection on Previous Proposal

The previous proposal, while grounded in existing literature, overlaps with ongoing work in spectral quantization and training-free optimization. For instance, the concept of **Spectral Quantization Routing (SQR)** has been proposed, which focuses on dynamic precision allocation based on real-time activation geometry. This indicates a need for a different approach that adds substantial novelty while maintaining empirical rigor.

### New Proposal Idea

The refined proposal will focus on a novel mechanism for enhancing the stability and efficiency of training-free inference in neural networks by leveraging geometric properties of activation spaces during runtime. The core concept will revolve around the idea of **Adaptive Spectral Dilation**, where we explore how the geometric properties of the feature space can be manipulated to enhance model performance without retraining.

