    "Related Work": "Existing literature has focused on static optimization techniques and heuristic methods that often fail to adapt to dynamic environments. This proposal distinguishes itself by introducing a novel, real-time spectral diagnostic approach that integrates seamlessly with layer-skipping protocols, providing both theoretical grounding and empirical validation.",
    "Abstract": "In the landscape of machine learning inference, latency-critical applications demand efficient computational strategies that minimize overhead while maximizing performance. We propose a novel framework, Dynamic Spectral Optimization (DSO), which leverages the spectral properties of activation spaces to inform a Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism. By computing real-time spectral diagnostics on hidden states, DSO dynamically routes tokens through fewer layers based on their stability characteristics, ensuring strict adherence to latency budgets. This training-free approach not only mitigates the risks associated with hidden-state perturbation but also enhances resource allocation efficiency. Grounded in PAC-Bayes theory, we establish theoretical links between spectral conditioning and generalization stability under perturbation. Initial experiments will benchmark DSO against established protocols across various datasets, measuring throughput-accuracy trade-offs and latency guarantees. This framework aims to set new standards for resource-efficient inference in machine learning applications.",
