    "Short Hypothesis": "By leveraging spectral properties of neural networks, we can develop a training-free adaptive quantization strategy that minimizes quantization error while maintaining computational efficiency, distinguishing our approach from existing heuristic and training-based methods.",
    "Related Work": "Current mixed-precision quantization methods primarily rely on either heuristic-based strategies or require extensive training cycles to optimize bit-width configurations, as seen in works like EMQ and SNIP. Our proposal seeks to utilize spectral properties of network weight distributions, which have not been extensively explored in this context, to provide a mathematically grounded, adaptive strategy that is both efficient and accurate.",
    "Abstract": "Mixed Precision Quantization (MPQ) has emerged as a crucial technique for deploying neural networks on resource-constrained devices. However, existing methods often rely on heuristics or heavy training, leading to inefficiencies or reliance on expert knowledge. We propose a novel framework called Adaptive Spectral Quantization (ASQ), which employs spectral analysis of neural network weights to inform adaptive bit-width allocation. By analyzing the spectral properties of weight distributions, ASQ dynamically allocates precision based on the importance of each layer, minimizing quantization-induced performance degradation without the need for retraining. Our method leverages a single forward pass to assess the spectral characteristics, thus ensuring computational efficiency. We demonstrate the efficacy of ASQ through extensive experiments on standard benchmarks, showing that it outperforms conventional training-free methods and achieves comparable performance to state-of-the-art retraining approaches at significantly lower computational costs.",
    "Experiments": [
