{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "pac_bayes_jacobian_skip",
    "Title": "Optimizing Inference Latency through PAC-Bayes Frameworks and Jacobian-Based Layer-Skipping",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By integrating PAC-Bayes principles with a Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism, we can achieve more efficient ML inference that guarantees strict latency constraints while minimizing hidden-state perturbation.",
    "Related Work": "Existing literature focuses on either PAC-Bayes frameworks or layer-skipping methods for inference optimization, but there is a lack of studies that combine these approaches to address latency-critical inference with bounded overhead protocols.",
    "Abstract": "In the quest for efficient machine learning inference, balancing accuracy with strict latency requirements remains a significant challenge. This proposal investigates the integration of PAC-Bayes frameworks with a Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism to optimize inference latency while ensuring robust performance. By formulating the inference process as a bounded overhead protocol, we aim to minimize hidden-state perturbation and provide explicit guarantees on latency. The proposed method will be empirically validated through experiments designed to benchmark latency against accuracy, exploring the Pareto frontier of throughput and performance. We anticipate that this innovative approach will yield new insights into the scalability of ML models in latency-critical applications, paving the way for efficient deployment in real-world scenarios.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Experiment 1: Implement the Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism in a standard neural network architecture. Measure latency and accuracy using a test dataset, comparing results with traditional inference methods.",
