Arguments: {"idea":{"Name":"adaptive_jacobian_quantization","Title":"Adaptive Jacobian-Based Mixed Precision Quantization for Efficient Inference","Short Hypothesis":"Exploring a novel framework that leverages Jacobian-based sensitivity analysis to adaptively determine mixed precision quantization for neural networks, aiming to enhance inference efficiency while maintaining accuracy. This approach is particularly relevant as existing methods predominantly rely on static or heuristic quantization strategies that often overlook layer-wise sensitivity dynamics, leading to potential performance trade-offs.","Related Work":"Current literature on mixed precision quantization focuses primarily on uniform precision strategies or heuristic-based adaptive methods that do not account for the dynamic nature of neural network activations. For instance, SliM-LLM employs salience-driven approaches but lacks a mathematical foundation linking Jacobian dynamics to quantization strategies. In contrast, our proposal uniquely integrates Jacobian sensitivity with adaptive quantization to provide a more principled and theoretically grounded approach, distinguishing it from existing works in the domain.","Abstract":"In this proposal, we introduce an innovative framework for adaptive mixed precision quantization that utilizes Jacobian-based sensitivity analysis to optimize bit-width allocations dynamically across layers of neural networks. By assessing the impact of changes in input on the output layer via Jacobian matrices, we can determine which layers are most sensitive to quantization errors and allocate precision accordingly. This approach not only minimizes quantization-induced accuracy degradation but also aligns with the growing need for efficient inference in latency-critical applications. Our experiments will demonstrate the effectiveness of this framework against traditional methods, showcasing improvements in both computational efficiency and model accuracy. We will implement this framework in a series of standard neural architectures and evaluate it using established benchmarks, with a focus on deriving clear, reproducible results that can be easily adapted across different model types.","Experiments":"1. Implement the Jacobian-based adaptive quantization framework on standard neural networks (e.g., ResNet, BERT). \n2. Compare performance metrics (accuracy, inference speed, memory usage) against static and heuristic quantization methods. \n3. Conduct ablation studies to assess the impact of Jacobian sensitivity on quantization decisions. \n4. Use datasets such as ImageNet and GLUE to evaluate the proposed method under various conditions. \n5. Metrics: Top-1 accuracy, inference latency (milliseconds), memory footprint (MB).","Risk Factors and Limitations":"Potential limitations include the computational overhead associated with calculating Jacobians, which may negate some efficiency gains. Additionally, the performance of the proposed method could vary significantly across different architectures, and extensive tuning may be required to optimize the quantization strategy for each specific model."}}
