### Proposal

IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_layer_dependency_mixed_precision",
    "Title": "Adaptive Layer-Dependency Mixed Precision Quantization for Efficient Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By integrating activation importance and layer dependency analysis into a training-free mixed-precision quantization framework, significant gains in inference efficiency and accuracy can be achieved without the need for retraining models.",
    "Related Work": "Previous works like SNIP and SliM-LLM have focused on adaptive mixed-precision quantization; however, they often overlook inter-layer dependencies and dynamic activation importance. Our approach builds on the foundational principles of these methods while introducing a novel layer-aware importance metric that is training-free and adaptable to various architectures, making it distinct and innovative.",
    "Abstract": "The deployment of large-scale neural networks often requires efficient inference strategies, particularly through mixed-precision quantization. While previous methods have achieved promising results, they frequently rely on retraining or fixed optimization strategies that may not generalize well across different model architectures or workloads. We propose a novel framework for training-free mixed-precision quantization that dynamically assesses activation importance across layers, enabling adaptive bit-width allocation based on both activation significance and inter-layer dependencies. Our method utilizes a layer-aware importance metric derived from spectral stability properties, allowing for effective quantization without the need for extensive retraining. Initial evaluations demonstrate that our framework can significantly enhance inference speed while maintaining accuracy, positioning it as a valuable tool for deploying large models in resource-constrained environments. The proposed method will be validated across various neural network architectures and datasets, emphasizing its versatility and robustness in practical applications.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Conduct a series of experiments on diverse neural network architectures (e.g., ResNet, ViT) to quantitatively assess the impact of the proposed layer-aware importance metric on mixed-precision quantization.",
      "2. Evaluate the performance of the framework under varying data distributions to analyze its adaptability and robustness.",
      "3. Compare the proposed method's inference speed and accuracy against existing state-of-the-art mixed-precision methods, focusing on both training-free and training-dependent approaches.",
      "4. Measure the latency and memory usage during inference to establish a comprehensive understanding of the efficiency gains.",
