    "Abstract": "In the realm of machine learning, real-time applications demand not only high accuracy but also stringent latency constraints. While adaptive mixed precision techniques have advanced the training process, they often fall short in optimizing inference performance. This paper proposes a novel framework for Adaptive Mixed Precision Inference (AMPI) that leverages PAC-Bayes theory to dynamically adjust precision levels during inference based on real-time performance metrics. By evaluating activation and latency-sensitive layers, AMPI applies a Jacobian-based layer-skipping strategy that minimizes hidden-state perturbations while adhering to strict wall-clock budgets. We will empirically validate our framework through a series of experiments on benchmark datasets, focusing on throughput-accuracy trade-offs. The results will highlight the efficacy of AMPI in achieving latency-critical performance without the overhead of retraining, thus presenting a significant advancement in the field of machine learning inference.",
