    "Name": "dynamic_precision_allocation",
    "Title": "Dynamic Precision Allocation via Real-Time Activation Geometry for Latency-Critical Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "We hypothesize that real-time analysis of activation geometry can effectively inform dynamic precision allocation strategies, improving both throughput and accuracy under strict latency constraints. This approach addresses the limitations of existing static and heuristic precision allocation methods by leveraging the properties of activation subspaces.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works such as 'Spectral Quantization Routing' propose dynamic precision allocation based on activation covariance but typically rely on static profiling. Our proposed method distinguishes itself by implementing a training-free, real-time approach that continuously adapts to variations in input distributions while enforcing strict latency budgets, thus avoiding the pitfalls of static methods.",
    "Abstract": "In latency-critical machine learning applications, efficient resource allocation is paramount. Traditional precision allocation methods often fail to adapt to dynamic input distributions, leading to either unnecessary computational overhead or degraded model performance. We propose a novel framework for dynamic precision allocation that utilizes real-time activation geometry to inform precision decisions on-the-fly. By analyzing local covariance structures of activations, our method identifies tokens that require varying levels of numerical precision based on their geometric properties. This training-free approach ensures that the model maintains strict latency constraints while optimizing throughput-accuracy trade-offs. We will evaluate this framework across multiple latency-sensitive benchmarks, establishing a new paradigm for resource-efficient inference that is both empirically validated and theoretically grounded in PAC-Bayes frameworks. Our results are anticipated to set a new standard for dynamic precision allocation in machine learning, paving the way for wider adoption in real-world applications.",
    "Experiments": [
