    "Title": "Optimizing Latency in Machine Learning Inference through Jacobian-Based Layer Skipping with PAC-Bayes Guarantees",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Leveraging Jacobian-based layer skipping can enhance real-time machine learning inference performance while maintaining PAC-Bayes generalization guarantees, addressing both latency and accuracy in critical applications.",
    "Related Work": "Current literature explores latency reduction in ML inference through various optimization techniques; however, few integrate Jacobian-based methodologies with PAC-Bayes frameworks. Existing studies like 'Randomized Pairwise Learning with Adaptive Sampling' focus on adaptive sampling for training but do not address inference latency or the mechanistic transparency of layer skipping. This proposal distinguishes itself by applying a rigorous framework that combines Jacobian insights with PAC-Bayes guarantees in a cohesive manner.",
    "Abstract": "In this proposal, we investigate a novel approach to optimize latency in machine learning inference by employing a Jacobian-based layer-skipping framework integrated with PAC-Bayes principles. As machine learning applications increasingly demand real-time performance, the ability to minimize inference latency without sacrificing accuracy becomes paramount. We hypothesize that strategically skipping layers in neural networks based on Jacobian evaluations can lead to significant reductions in computational overhead while ensuring adherence to PAC-Bayes generalization guarantees. Our approach will involve developing a mechanistic understanding of layer contributions and their impact on output variance, facilitating informed decisions about layer retention or skipping during inference. We aim to validate this hypothesis through a series of experiments that evaluate the trade-offs between latency and accuracy across various architectures under strict computational constraints. This work promises to advance the field by providing a robust framework for low-latency machine learning inference.",
