    "Short Hypothesis": "By reformulating the problem of mixed-precision quantization as a quantization proxy quantification task, we can derive a simple yet effective training-free method that utilizes layer-wise sensitivity analysis and quantization error propagation to generate optimal bit-width configurations.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works such as EMQ and DQT focus on training-free methods for mixed-precision quantization, but they rely heavily on evolutionary algorithms or heuristic-based sensitivity metrics that often fail to generalize well across different architectures. Our approach will distinguish itself by employing a quantization proxy quantification technique that directly assesses the influence of layer sensitivities on the overall quantization error without requiring extensive training or expert knowledge.",
    "Abstract": "In the realm of mixed-precision quantization (MPQ), many existing strategies struggle with the balance between performance and computational efficiency, particularly under training-free constraints. We propose a novel framework, Quantization Proxy Quantification (QPQ), which reformulates the quantization optimization problem into a quantification task focused on layer-wise sensitivity analysis. By leveraging deterministic spectral estimators and quantization error propagation models, QPQ quantifies the impact of each layer's precision configuration on the overall model accuracy without requiring training. Our method systematically evaluates the sensitivity of each layer to quantization errors, enabling dynamic adjustment of bit-width configurations across the network. Preliminary experiments will validate our approach on standard datasets and architectures, targeting significant reductions in computational overhead while preserving model performance. This approach aims to offer a simple, interpretable, and effective mechanism for optimizing mixed-precision models in resource-constrained environments.",
