{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_mixed_precision_for_latency_optimization",
    "Title": "Optimizing Latency-Accuracy Trade-offs with Adaptive Mixed-Precision Quantization for LLM Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Adaptive mixed-precision quantization can significantly enhance inference performance in latency-sensitive applications without compromising model accuracy, particularly by leveraging layer-wise sensitivity analysis to dynamically adjust precision during runtime.",
    "Related Work": "While existing methods like KVTuner and Cocktail focus on KV cache quantization and mixed-precision techniques, they often overlook the dynamic adjustments necessary for real-time inference. My proposal addresses this by integrating a layer-wise sensitivity framework that adapts precision based on runtime context, thus providing a more efficient solution that is not just a static application of quantization.",
    "Abstract": "In the realm of large language models, efficient inference remains a critical challenge, particularly in latency-sensitive applications. This proposal introduces a novel framework for adaptive mixed-precision quantization that dynamically adjusts the precision of model layers during inference based on their sensitivity to quantization errors. By implementing a layer-wise sensitivity analysis, the proposed method enables real-time adjustments to bit-width configurations, optimizing the latency-accuracy trade-off. We aim to conduct experiments on standard LLMs, measuring performance improvements in both inference speed and resource efficiency. Our approach seeks to establish new benchmarks for mixed-precision quantization techniques, demonstrating significant reductions in latency while maintaining or even improving model accuracy. The implications of this research extend to various applications requiring efficient deployment of LLMs, paving the way for future advancements in real-time AI systems.",
