  "idea": {
    "Name": "dynamic_precision_allocation",
    "Title": "Dynamic Precision Allocation via Spectral Geometry for Efficient Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "We hypothesize that real-time geometric diagnostics of activation covariances can dynamically inform numerical precision allocation, optimizing inference without training.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works have explored mixed-precision inference and training-free optimization; however, they often rely on static profiling or heuristic methods. Our approach distinguishes itself by employing a geometric framework that adapts precision based on the local condition number of activations, thus ensuring robustness to distributional shifts.",
    "Abstract": "Mixed-precision inference is a promising avenue for improving the efficiency of machine learning models, yet it often suffers from static calibration methods that fail to adapt to varying input distributions. We propose a novel, training-free framework for dynamic numerical precision allocation that leverages real-time spectral geometry diagnostics of hidden states. By computing local covariance condition numbers and spectral decay rates, we can directly inform precision requirements for tokens during inference. Our hypothesis is that well-conditioned, rapidly decaying subspaces can tolerate lower precision, while ill-conditioned tokens necessitate higher precision to maintain performance. We evaluate this framework on diverse benchmarks in single-GPU settings, demonstrating significant latency and resource efficiency gains. The results will provide insights into the mathematical relationship between activation geometry and inference stability, paving the way for transparent, scalable solutions in mixed-precision machine learning.",
