```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "dynamic_spectral_precision_routing",
    "Title": "Dynamic Spectral Precision Routing: A Training-Free Approach to Latency-Aware Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "We hypothesize that leveraging real-time spectral analysis of activation patterns can dynamically adjust computational precision and routing paths, optimizing performance under strict latency constraints without the need for retraining.",
    "Related Work": "Existing frameworks like Spectral Quantization Routing (SQR) and Training-Free Geometric Interference Cancellation focus on static or semi-static approaches to inference optimization. Our proposal distinguishes itself by introducing a fully dynamic routing mechanism based on spectral properties of hidden states, adapting to real-time input conditions, thereby enhancing robustness and efficiency in latency-critical environments.",
    "Abstract": "In the pursuit of efficient machine learning inference, enforcing strict latency budgets while maintaining accuracy remains a critical challenge. We propose 'Dynamic Spectral Precision Routing,' a training-free mechanism that leverages real-time spectral analysis of activation patterns to dynamically adjust numerical precision and routing paths during inference. By analyzing the spectral decay and covariance condition numbers of hidden states, our method intelligently allocates computational resources where they are most needed, ensuring optimal performance under varying input distributions. Unlike existing frameworks that rely on static precision allocation, our approach adapts to the nuance of real-time data, allowing for fine-grained control over inference processes. We will evaluate this framework across multiple benchmarks, measuring throughput, accuracy, and latency, establishing a new standard for resource-efficient inference that directly links spectral properties to operational performance.",
