    "Title": "Dynamic Latency-Optimized Inference Routing via Activation Spectral Analysis",
    "Short Hypothesis": "We propose a training-free inference routing mechanism that utilizes real-time spectral analysis of hidden states to dynamically allocate computation paths in neural networks, achieving strict latency targets while optimizing resource usage, thus distinguishing it from existing methods that rely on static routing or heuristic adjustments.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works such as Spectral Quantization Routing (SQR) and Geometric Signal Separation primarily focus on static profiling or training-based adjustments for inference efficiency. Our approach diverges by introducing a real-time, training-free mechanism that dynamically routes computation based on spectral properties of activations, providing a more adaptive and theoretically grounded solution for latency-critical applications.",
    "Abstract": "In the realm of machine learning inference, achieving a balance between computational efficiency and strict latency constraints remains a formidable challenge. We introduce a novel framework for dynamic latency-optimized inference routing that leverages real-time spectral analysis of hidden states to inform computational decisions without requiring additional training. Our method computes the spectral decay rates and condition numbers of activations on-the-fly to categorize tokens based on their computational needs. By adapting inference paths dynamically, we ensure that computational resources are allocated efficiently, adhering to strict latency budgets while maintaining accuracy. We establish theoretical connections between the spectral properties of activations and PAC-Bayes generalization bounds, demonstrating that our approach not only enhances robustness against distributional shifts but also provides a transparent mechanism for managing resource allocation. Through extensive evaluation on standard benchmarks, we will illustrate the effectiveness of our proposed routing framework in comparison to static and heuristic strategies, ultimately delivering a compute-frugal solution that meets the demands of real-world applications.",
