    "Related Work": "Existing approaches like EMQ focus on evolving proxies for mixed-precision quantization but often lack a clear understanding of the underlying correlation between proxy design and quantization accuracy. This proposal uniquely combines evolutionary techniques with a dynamic adaptation mechanism, aiming to optimize quantization across varying layers and model architectures while remaining training-free.",
    "Abstract": "In the quest for efficient mixed-precision quantization, current methods either rely on heuristic-based tuning or training-intensive search algorithms, limiting their adaptability and efficiency. This proposal introduces a novel framework for dynamically evolving training-free proxies for mixed-precision quantization, leveraging evolutionary algorithms to explore a diverse proxy space. By employing a fitness function that incorporates metrics of quantization accuracy and model performance, our approach aims to discover optimal bit-width configurations that adapt over time to different model architectures and data distributions. This dynamic adaptation not only enhances the quantization process but also reduces the computational burden associated with traditional methods. We will validate our framework through a series of experiments on standard datasets, demonstrating improved efficiency and accuracy in model deployment. Our findings promise to advance the state-of-the-art in mixed-precision quantization, paving the way for more efficient AI systems capable of operating within constrained environments.",
