    "Related Work": "Recent works have explored geometric manipulations in learning frameworks, such as Spectral Latent Steering, which emphasizes low-rank projections during inference to enhance reasoning capabilities. However, there remains limited exploration into dynamic geometric filtering strategies that can isolate task-relevant signals from noisy contexts in a training-free manner. This proposal expands on these concepts by explicitly connecting geometric signal separation with in-context learning stability.",
    "Abstract": "In-context learning (ICL) allows language models to adapt to new tasks without parameter updates, yet their performance can degrade under distributional shifts and noisy input contexts. We propose a novel training-free framework that employs geometric signal separation techniques to enhance the robustness of ICL. By analyzing the local covariance of activation spaces, we can isolate high-variance principal components that capture task-relevant signals while filtering out low-variance noise. This method involves a simple PCA-based projection applied dynamically during inference, enabling models to maintain performance even under challenging conditions. We will empirically evaluate this approach across various ICL benchmarks, measuring accuracy retention and inference efficiency. Our findings aim to establish a direct link between geometric properties of hidden states and model resilience, offering a mathematically grounded pathway for enhancing ICL in real-world applications.",
