    "Related Work": "While previous work has focused on training-free methods like NEAR and Spectral Latent Steering, they often rely on latent space projections or heuristic optimizations. Our approach distinguishes itself by proposing a geometric filtering method that specifically isolates high-variance principal components from noisy activations, enabling a more direct mechanism for improving model robustness in real-time applications.",
    "Abstract": "In the context of large language models (LLMs) and other sophisticated machine learning systems, robustness to adversarial inputs and distributional shifts remains a critical challenge. We propose a novel training-free geometric filtering framework that utilizes principal component analysis (PCA) to isolate high-variance signal directions from low-variance noise within model activations during inference. By projecting activations onto the top-k principal components derived from initial layer activations, we enhance the model's ability to focus on relevant task signals, thereby improving performance on adversarial and out-of-distribution benchmarks. Our experiments will evaluate the effectiveness of this approach across various datasets, measuring accuracy retention, inference efficiency, and robustness to noise. We further establish a direct link between the variance of principal components and computational resource allocation, enabling dynamic early-exit strategies that optimize inference speed. This work bridges mechanistic interpretability with practical efficiency, offering a mathematically grounded method for enhancing model reliability in constrained environments.",
