    "Related Work": "Recent works such as Spectral Quantization Routing and Geometric Signal Separation have explored the use of spectral properties for optimizing inference. However, these approaches primarily focus on quantization and noise separation, respectively, lacking a comprehensive framework that integrates real-time adaptive routing of inference paths based on spectral diagnostics. Our proposal distinguishes itself by dynamically adjusting layer utilization based on the spectral characteristics of activation distributions during inference, providing a novel, training-free method for latency-critical applications.",
    "Abstract": "In this work, we introduce Adaptive Spectral Inference (ASI), a training-free framework that optimizes inference performance by dynamically adjusting layer utilization based on the spectral properties of model activations. By analyzing the covariance structure of activations at inference time, ASI facilitates real-time decision-making regarding which layers to execute, effectively reducing computational overhead while adhering to strict latency budgets. We build on foundational PAC-Bayes principles to ground our method in theoretical guarantees of performance and generalization. Initial experiments will evaluate ASI across various latency-sensitive benchmarks in natural language processing and computer vision, measuring throughput, accuracy, and latency. Our approach aims to bridge the gap between spectral analysis and practical inference optimization, offering a scalable solution for deploying machine learning models in resource-constrained environments.",
