    "Related Work": "Previous work has explored training-free methods for optimizing inference, such as Spectral Quantization Routing and Geometric Signal Separation. However, these approaches primarily focus on static properties of activations or rely on heuristic methods. In contrast, our proposal aims to employ real-time spectral diagnostics to dynamically adjust inference paths, ensuring strict latency adherence while minimizing overhead.",
    "Abstract": "In the context of latency-critical applications, optimizing inference pathways in machine learning models presents a significant challenge. This proposal introduces 'Dynamic Inference Control' (DIC), a training-free framework that exploits real-time spectral properties of hidden activations to manage inference paths dynamically. By analyzing the spectral condition number and decay rate of activation covariance, DIC enables the model to selectively skip or prioritize layers based on the current input's complexity and the desired latency budget. We aim to establish a robust framework that guarantees strict wall-clock timing while improving computational efficiency. Through a series of experiments on diverse benchmarks, we will evaluate the effectiveness of DIC in maintaining performance while adhering to latency constraints. This work will bridge the gap between dynamic inference optimization and rigorous theoretical grounding, providing a reproducible method for implementing real-time inference control in resource-constrained environments.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Implement DIC in a standard neural architecture (e.g., a transformer) and compare it against a baseline model without dynamic control under various latency constraints.",
      "2. Measure accuracy, throughput, and latency across different input complexities using a diverse set of datasets.",
