    "Name": "jacobian_layer_skipping",
    "Title": "Optimizing Latency-Aware Inference through Jacobian-Based Layer Skipping",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Employing a Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism can enhance the latency-aware inference capabilities of neural networks while maintaining accuracy and minimizing resource usage.",
    "Related Work": "Existing literature primarily focuses on energy efficiency or latency in isolation. Notable works include frameworks for carbon-aware optimization and lightweight ML for edge devices, but none have effectively integrated a Jacobian-based approach for real-time layer skipping under strict latency constraints, representing a significant gap this research aims to fill.",
    "Abstract": "In the quest for efficient and responsive machine learning systems, the challenge of balancing inference latency and computational overhead remains paramount. This proposal introduces a novel Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism for latency-aware inference in neural networks. By analyzing the Jacobian of the network's activations, we can determine the necessity of processing each layer based on a user-defined latency budget. This approach enables dynamic layer selection during inference, thereby reducing computation in scenarios where full network depth is unnecessary. We aim to empirically validate this mechanism against traditional inference methods, analyzing its impact on accuracy, latency, and resource consumption. Our experiments will benchmark performance across various architectures and datasets, underscoring the potential of our method to push the boundaries of efficient deep learning deployment in latency-critical environments.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Implement a baseline neural network model and a variant using the Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism.",
      "2. Evaluate the models on several datasets, measuring accuracy, inference latency, and resource consumption in a controlled environment.",
