    "Name": "adaptive_mixed_precision_through_spectral_analysis",
    "Title": "Adaptive Mixed Precision Quantization Using Spectral Analysis for Efficient Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Can spectral analysis of layer-wise gradients improve the accuracy of adaptive mixed-precision quantization without requiring extensive retraining?",
    "Related Work": "Existing frameworks like SNIP and AMP-ViT focus on adaptive mixed precision but primarily rely on heuristic methods or require extensive training phases. Our approach utilizes spectral analysis to derive precision requirements from the gradient landscape, allowing for a more mechanistic understanding of layer sensitivity to quantization without retraining, thus distinguishing it from current literature.",
    "Abstract": "As neural network models grow increasingly complex, efficient inference through mixed-precision quantization has become paramount. Existing methods often rely on cumbersome training processes or heuristic approaches that do not generalize effectively. In this proposal, we introduce a novel method leveraging spectral analysis of gradients in deep learning networks to determine the optimal bit-width for each layer adaptively. By analyzing the spectral properties of gradients during inference, we can derive a more accurate mapping of precision requirements, enabling a training-free adaptive mixed-precision quantization framework. This method promises to minimize computational overhead while maximizing model performance, achieving significant reductions in memory usage and latency. We will evaluate our framework against state-of-the-art mixed-precision techniques using established benchmarks, focusing on throughput-accuracy trade-offs, and explore the implications for deployment in resource-constrained environments.",
    "Experiments": [
