    "Title": "Geometric Proxies for Training-Free Mixed Precision Quantization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Leveraging geometric characteristics of neural network representations can yield superior training-free proxies for mixed precision quantization, enhancing accuracy and computational efficiency.",
    "Related Work": "Existing methods, such as EMQ and InfoQ, explore training-free approaches but primarily focus on heuristics or local sensitivity. This proposal diverges by introducing a geometric framework that emphasizes the role of representation geometry in determining the optimal bit-width allocation, thereby providing a more robust and theoretically grounded method.",
    "Abstract": "In the quest for efficient neural network deployment, quantization emerges as a key technique for reducing model size and computational demand. While significant advancements have been made in training-free mixed precision quantization, the relationship between geometric properties of neural representations and quantization accuracy remains underexplored. This proposal introduces a novel framework that utilizes geometric diagnostics—specifically curvature and gradient covariance decay—to derive training-free proxies for mixed precision quantization. By analyzing the subspace structure of neural representations, we can identify critical pathways that influence model performance under varying bit-width configurations. The proposed approach aims to establish a rigorous mathematical foundation for quantization strategies, ensuring stability and accuracy while minimizing computational overhead. We will validate our framework through a series of experiments across benchmark datasets, demonstrating the advantages of our geometric quantization proxies compared to existing heuristic-based methods.",
