### Revised Proposal

IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "quantization_geometry",
    "Title": "Geometric Insights for Training-Free Mixed-Precision Quantization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Can we leverage geometric properties of weight distributions to design a training-free mixed-precision quantization framework that guarantees improved accuracy while maintaining computational efficiency?",
    "Related Work": "Current literature on mixed-precision quantization, such as EMQ and InfoQ, primarily focuses on heuristic-driven approaches or heavy computational requirements for optimal bit-width configurations. Our proposal distinguishes itself by utilizing geometric insights from weight distributions, establishing a deterministic framework that operates without the need for training cycles, thus simplifying the process and improving efficiency.",
    "Abstract": "In the realm of mixed-precision quantization, existing methods often rely on training-based search techniques that can be computationally intensive and time-consuming. This proposal introduces a novel framework that utilizes geometric properties of neural network weight distributions to inform mixed-precision quantization strategies. By analyzing the curvature and distribution of weights in the high-dimensional space of models, we can derive deterministic quantization policies that maximize accuracy while minimizing computational overhead. This training-free approach not only simplifies the quantization process but also provides a transparent and interpretable methodology for model optimization. Through empirical validation on benchmark datasets, we aim to demonstrate the efficacy of our geometric insights, comparing our approach against leading mixed-precision methods in terms of accuracy, efficiency, and computational requirements.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Conduct a spectral analysis of weight distributions across various layers of popular architectures (ResNet, MobileNet) to identify curvature properties.",
      "2. Develop a geometric quantization strategy based on these properties, defining a deterministic mapping from weight distributions to optimal bit-width configurations.",
      "3. Evaluate the proposed method on standard benchmarks (ImageNet, COCO) comparing accuracy and computational efficiency against existing mixed-precision methods.",
      "4. Measure the stability of quantization outcomes across multiple runs to assess robustness and reproducibility."
