    "Title": "Environment-Aware Adaptive Mixed-Precision Quantization for Latency-Sensitive Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Integrating real-time environmental feedback into mixed-precision quantization can enhance model performance and efficiency in latency-critical applications, surpassing existing methods that utilize static or heuristic-based strategies.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works primarily focus on static mixed-precision methods, often neglecting runtime variability and environmental conditions. For example, methods like SNIP and SliM-LLM focus on layer-wise precision adjustments but do not account for real-time changes in inference conditions. This proposal introduces dynamic adaptations based on feedback from the execution environment, distinguishing it from previous efforts.",
    "Abstract": "In the realm of machine learning, mixed-precision quantization has emerged as a vital technique for optimizing model performance, particularly in latency-sensitive applications. However, existing approaches often apply static quantization policies that do not adapt to changing operational conditions, leading to inefficiencies. This work proposes a novel framework for environment-aware adaptive mixed-precision quantization, which integrates real-time feedback from inference environments into the quantization process. By leveraging dynamic environmental parameters such as compute availability and workload characteristics, the proposed method adapts the precision of model parameters on-the-fly, optimizing both latency and accuracy. We will validate this approach through rigorous experiments across various architectures and deployment scenarios, establishing new benchmarks for efficiency in large model inference.",
