    "Related Work": "Previous studies on PAC-Bayes and spectral stability have primarily focused on traditional model settings. Our proposal distinguishes itself by directly applying these frameworks to latent variable models, which have not been sufficiently explored in this context. Moreover, existing work tends to overlook the implications of spectral stability on inference efficiency and overhead.",
    "Abstract": "This research proposes a novel framework for optimizing latent variable models by leveraging spectral stability and PAC-Bayes bounds. The objective is to enhance inference performance while ensuring strictly bounded computational overhead. We will develop a Jacobian-based layer-skipping mechanism that explicitly targets spectral stability during the inference phase. By integrating uncertainty-quantified activation proxies, we aim to establish a latency-aware design that minimizes hidden-state perturbation and enforces strict wall-clock budgets. We will conduct experiments to validate the effectiveness of our approach against benchmark latent variable models, focusing on throughput-accuracy trade-offs and stability metrics. Our findings will contribute to the development of more efficient and scalable latent variable models in real-world applications.",
