To propose a novel research idea, I will focus on the concept of a Kernel Performance Tuner (KPT) that dynamically adjusts kernel parameters and configurations during inference based on real-time profiling data. This system would leverage heuristics derived from hardware performance metrics, allowing the inference engine to adapt to changing workload characteristics and hardware states. The key innovation here is the real-time adjustment of kernel execution parameters (like tile sizes, data layouts, and precision) rather than relying on static configurations or pre-optimized kernels.

This idea distinguishes itself from existing work by integrating a feedback loop that continuously tunes kernel execution based on actual performance metrics, rather than solely relying on pre-computed, hardware-agnostic optimizations. By focusing on real-time adjustments, the KPT can exploit transient hardware states and workload variations, potentially yielding better performance than static optimizations.

