    "Related Work": "Current research has primarily focused on adaptive mixed-precision quantization without a comprehensive connection to theoretical limits. Works like QARV and SNIP provide practical implementations but lack the rigorous exploration of rate-distortion principles in quantization. This proposal will provide a theoretical framework that connects quantization choices to achievable rates and distortion, offering insights that existing empirical methods do not.",
    "Abstract": "In this research, we propose a novel exploration of quantization in neural networks framed through the lens of rate-distortion theory. We hypothesize that by systematically analyzing the trade-offs between quantization levels and predictive sufficiency, we can derive optimal quantization strategies that adhere to information-theoretic limits. Our approach will involve establishing a framework that quantifies the relationship between quantization rates and the resulting distortion in model performance, leading to a deeper understanding of the fundamental bit-cost associated with various quantization configurations. Through a series of experiments, we will validate our theoretical findings by comparing the performance of our proposed quantization strategies against state-of-the-art methods, providing a comprehensive evaluation of their efficiency in relation to established information-theoretic bounds.",
    "Experiments": [
