    "Related Work": "Current literature, including works on model pruning and mixed-precision quantization, primarily addresses empirical strategies for compression without establishing a clear theoretical framework linking quantization distortion to task performance. This proposal distinguishes itself by providing a formal characterization of the quantization process as a lossy source coding problem, exploring how optimal quantization strategies can be derived from task-specific information measures.",
    "Abstract": "In this work, we propose a novel framework that investigates the relationship between quantization strategies in model compression and their impact on task-relevant performance. We frame quantization as a lossy source coding problem under a distortion constraint defined by task performance metrics. By leveraging information-theoretic principles, we will derive a set of achievable bounds on the bits-per-weight necessary to maintain predictive sufficiency while quantizing neural network weights. We hypothesize that aligning the quantization process with the task's information landscape can lead to more efficient compression schemes. Our approach will include both theoretical derivations of the quantization-task alignment and empirical validation through experiments on standard datasets. The outcomes of this research will provide insights into optimal quantization strategies, bridging the gap between theoretical limits and practical implementations in model compression.",
