    "Related Work": "Existing works primarily focus on empirical methods for pruning and quantization without a rigorous theoretical framework. Notable examples include 'An Information-Theoretic Justification for Model Pruning' and 'Probabilistic Automated Model Compression', which address compression but often miss the dynamic adjustment of compression rates based on activation distributions.",
    "Abstract": "This proposal introduces a novel information-theoretic framework for dynamic neural network compression, treating the network as a communication channel where the objective is to maximize mutual information between inputs and outputs under a rate constraint. We formalize the relationship between model complexity, quantization, and pruning as a rate-distortion problem, deriving achievable rates and bounds on the compression efficiency. Through theoretical analysis and empirical validation, we aim to demonstrate that our framework can adaptively allocate resources to maintain predictive performance while minimizing model size. Key experiments will involve evaluating various neural architectures across standard datasets, measuring the trade-off between compression rates and task performance. This work aims to bridge the gap between information theory and practical model deployment, providing a principled approach to neural network optimization.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Derive theoretical bounds on the achievable rate for various neural network architectures and datasets.",
      "2. Implement a dynamic pruning algorithm based on the sensitivity of activations, measuring distortion against predictive performance.",
      "3. Evaluate quantization strategies that allocate bit budgets according to mutual information estimates, comparing against baseline methods.",
