### Refined Proposal

IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "rate_distortion_adaptive_pruning",
    "Title": "Adaptive Pruning via Rate-Distortion Theory: A New Perspective",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By formulating adaptive pruning as a rate-distortion problem, we can optimize the bit-cost of model representations while minimizing task-relevant distortion, leading to improved model efficiency.",
    "Related Work": "While current works like 'Successive Pruning for Model Compression via Rate Distortion Theory' explore pruning, they often don't investigate the adaptive mechanisms based on task-relevant distortion. Our approach distinguishes itself by integrating a dynamic pruning strategy informed by real-time estimates of rate-distortion trade-offs, aiming for optimal efficiency without predefined thresholds.",
    "Abstract": "Model compression remains a critical challenge in the deployment of deep learning models. Recent advancements have framed model compression within the context of rate-distortion theory, but few have explored adaptive strategies that adjust the compression based on the task relevance of features. This proposal introduces a novel adaptive pruning mechanism that utilizes real-time estimates of the rate-distortion trade-off to dynamically prune model weights during inference. By leveraging mutual information and entropy measures, we will develop a framework that continuously assesses the task-relevant distortion caused by pruning, allowing for an optimal balance between model size and predictive accuracy. We will validate our approach through simulations on various architectures, focusing on the achievable bounds of compression without significant loss of performance. This research aims to provide a quantitative understanding of adaptive pruning strategies grounded in information theory, contributing to the development of more efficient and interpretable models.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Implement a baseline pruning algorithm based on fixed thresholds for model weights.",
      "Develop an adaptive pruning algorithm that utilizes estimated mutual information to inform pruning decisions.",
      "Evaluate both algorithms on benchmark datasets, measuring performance in terms of accuracy, bits-per-weight, and task-relevant distortion.",
      "Graph the rate-distortion curves to visualize the trade-offs and validate theoretical predictions."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": [
      "The adaptive pruning algorithm may introduce overhead that negates efficiency gains.",
      "Real-time estimates of mutual information could be computationally intensive.",
      "Generalizability across different architectures may vary, necessitating further optimization."
    ]
  }
}
