{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_kernel_tuning",
    "Title": "Adaptive Kernel Tuning for Quantized LLM Inference Optimization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By implementing an adaptive kernel tuning framework that utilizes real-time profiling data from GPU executions, we can achieve substantial performance improvements in quantized LLM inference without relying on predefined heuristics or training-based methods.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works focus heavily on theoretical frameworks and training-based optimizations for quantization. For instance, 'EMQ' explores training-free proxies but does not directly utilize real-time kernel profiling to adaptively tune performance. Our approach distinguishes itself by employing a hardware-centric adaptation strategy to optimize kernels based on empirical performance metrics, rather than relying on static configurations or heuristic methods.",
    "Abstract": "In this proposal, we introduce an Adaptive Kernel Tuning (AKT) framework designed specifically for optimizing quantized inference in large language models (LLMs). Our framework leverages real-time profiling data from GPU executions to dynamically adjust kernel parameters, such as tile sizes and precision levels, based on actual performance metrics like wall-clock latency and throughput. Unlike existing methods that apply fixed heuristics or training-based adjustments, AKT continuously learns and adapts to the specific characteristics of the model and input data. We will measure performance gains via p50/p99 latency, tokens-per-second, and energy per token on commodity GPUs, providing a clear empirical basis for our claims. This hardware-first approach aims to push the limits of efficiency in LLM inference, ensuring that the optimizations are grounded in real-world performance rather than theoretical conjectures.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Implement the AKT framework on a widely used quantized LLM, such as LLaMA.",
      "Conduct A/B tests comparing the adaptive tuning against baseline static configurations across different workloads.",
