    "Related Work": "Existing work, such as 'Rate Distortion For Model Compression: From Theory To Practice' (Gao et al., 2018) provides a foundational analysis but primarily focuses on linear models and does not extend to deep architectures or non-linearities prevalent in modern ML. Our work distinguishes itself by exploring a broader class of models, incorporating non-linear architectures, and deriving new bounds that can be empirically verified across various tasks.",
    "Abstract": "Model compression is crucial for deploying deep learning models on resource-constrained devices. While empirical approaches have achieved success in quantization and pruning, they often lack a theoretical underpinning that delineates the limits of compression. This paper proposes a novel rate-distortion framework that quantifies the bit-cost of compressing neural networks while preserving predictive performance. We derive new bounds on the achievable rates for compressing non-linear models and establish a connection between mutual information and task-relevant distortion. Our findings suggest that strategically allocating bits based on the information bottleneck can lead to significant improvements in both compression efficiency and model performance. We will validate this framework through extensive experiments involving various architectures and datasets, demonstrating its applicability and robustness across different scenarios.",
