    "Related Work": "While existing works like 'Rate Distortion For Model Compression' and 'Radio: Rate-Distortion Optimization for Large Language Model Compression' explore rate-distortion in model compression, they often overlook the influence of task-specific relevance in deriving these bounds. This proposal distinguishes itself by integrating task relevance into the rate-distortion framework, thereby providing a more versatile tool for model compression strategies.",
    "Abstract": "The advent of deep learning has led to increasingly complex models that pose significant challenges in deployment due to their size and computational demands. Current approaches to model compression often apply generic rate-distortion principles without regard for the task-specific relevance of the model's parameters. This proposal aims to derive novel rate-distortion bounds that incorporate task-relevant features, thereby enabling a comprehensive understanding of how to allocate bits effectively in model compression. By establishing a framework that quantifies the mutual information between model parameters and task performance, we will provide a robust theoretical foundation for future compression techniques. We will validate our approach through a series of experiments that compare traditional compression methods with our task-oriented bounds, demonstrating superior performance in maintaining predictive accuracy while achieving optimal compression.",
