    "Name": "adaptive_kv_cache_quantization",
    "Title": "Adaptive KV Cache Quantization for Hardware-Focused Inference Optimization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Can adaptive, layer-wise quantization of KV caches in transformer architectures yield significant improvements in inference throughput without degrading accuracy, particularly in the context of heterogeneous hardware environments?",
    "Related Work": "Existing works primarily address mixed-precision quantization in a static manner, often neglecting the dynamic nature of inference workloads and specific hardware characteristics. For instance, KVTuner analyzes layer-wise sensitivity but does not adaptively optimize during runtime. Our proposal distinguishes itself by implementing a real-time adaptive quantization mechanism that tailors KV cache precision based on current hardware performance metrics, thus avoiding the pitfalls of fixed configurations.",
    "Abstract": "In this work, we propose a novel framework for adaptive KV cache quantization aimed at enhancing inference efficiency in transformer models. Current mixed-precision quantization methods often overlook the dynamic nature of inference tasks and hardware capabilities. Our framework leverages real-time profiling data to adjust KV cache precision on-the-fly, optimizing for throughput and accuracy while minimizing the overhead typically associated with fixed quantization strategies. We evaluate the impact of our adaptive approach on popular transformer architectures, focusing on metrics such as wall-clock latency, tokens-per-second, and energy consumption. Preliminary experiments suggest that our method can lead to substantial improvements in inference speed without compromising accuracy. By addressing the gap in existing literature regarding adaptive quantization, our framework aims to provide a practical solution for deploying efficient transformer models in real-world applications with varying hardware configurations.",
    "Experiments": [
