Based on the literature search results and the existing proposals, I will refine my initial research idea to ensure it is novel, high-impact, and aligned with the hardware-first systems approach.

### Reflection on the Initial Idea

The idea of optimizing the KV cache in large language models (LLMs) through a hybrid quantization-offloading technique is innovative and responds to the challenges posed by latency and memory constraints in modern inference systems. However, the literature indicates that similar themes are already being explored in various forms, such as the TailorKV framework and Q-Infer, which both tackle KV cache optimization and dynamic scheduling.

### New Proposal Idea

To carve out a new niche, I propose a focus on **Dynamic Kernel Fusion** strategies that adaptively optimize the execution of multiple kernel operations based on real-time workload characteristics in LLM inference. This contrasts with existing work that tends to focus on static optimization or relies on off-the-shelf kernel libraries without considering the dynamic interplay of workloads.

### Refined Proposal

I will now prepare the final proposal with a focus on the dynamic aspect of kernel execution and fusion, which leverages the specifics of runtime profiling to optimize performance on commodity GPUs.

