    "Name": "dynamic_kernel_fusion",
    "Title": "Dynamic Kernel Fusion for Adaptive LLM Inference Optimization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Leveraging real-time workload profiling to implement dynamic kernel fusion strategies can significantly reduce inference latency and improve throughput in LLMs on commodity GPUs.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works focus on static kernel optimization and KV cache strategies, such as TailorKV and Q-Infer. However, they neglect the dynamic nature of inference workloads and do not explore real-time kernel fusion based on workload profiling, which can lead to more efficient execution.",
    "Abstract": "The deployment of large language models (LLMs) faces significant challenges due to high latency and memory bandwidth demands. This proposal introduces a novel approach to optimize inference through Dynamic Kernel Fusion (DKF), which dynamically combines multiple kernel operations based on real-time profiling metrics obtained during execution. By continuously monitoring workload characteristics such as memory access patterns, compute intensity, and kernel launch overhead, DKF can adaptively fuse kernels to minimize latency and maximize throughput. We will implement this technique on a commodity GPU and evaluate its performance against traditional static kernel optimization methods. Our experiments will focus on quantifying wall-clock latency, throughput, and energy efficiency, demonstrating the advantages of adaptive execution strategies in LLM inference.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Implement a baseline LLM inference engine using static kernel optimizations.",
      "2. Develop a DKF strategy that profiles workload characteristics during inference and dynamically fuses compatible kernels.",
      "3. Conduct A/B latency races between the baseline and DKF implementation under various batch sizes and input complexities, measuring p50/p99 latency and throughput.",
