Based on the literature review, it is clear that there is a growing interest in optimizing GPU architectures for machine learning inference, particularly through techniques such as spatial partitioning and kernel optimization. However, existing work mainly focuses on high-level abstractions and multi-model serving, often overlooking the detailed kernel-level profiling and optimizations that can yield significant performance improvements for individual models.

**Proposed Research Idea:**
The novel idea I propose is to explore "Dynamic Kernel Fusion and Runtime Optimization" for GPU inference, which involves real-time profiling and dynamic adjustments to kernel execution based on performance metrics such as memory bandwidth utilization, occupancy, and kernel execution time. This approach would differ from existing works by centering on a dynamic optimization framework that continuously monitors and adapts to runtime conditions, rather than pre-defining kernel configurations or batch sizes.

### IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "dynamic_kernel_fusion",
    "Title": "Dynamic Kernel Fusion and Runtime Optimization for GPU Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Real-time profiling and dynamic kernel fusion can significantly enhance GPU inference performance by adapting execution parameters to current hardware conditions, leading to improved latency and throughput metrics.",
    "Related Work": "While existing literature like KRISP and multi-model inference systems explore GPU resource optimization and spatial partitioning, they typically do so statically. Our approach introduces a runtime optimization layer focused on kernel-level adjustments, addressing specific performance bottlenecks in real-time based on measured hardware performance metrics.",
    "Abstract": "This proposal introduces a novel framework for dynamic kernel fusion and runtime optimization in GPU inference systems. By utilizing real-time profiling data—such as occupancy, memory bandwidth utilization, and kernel execution time—we aim to develop a system that dynamically adjusts kernel parameters to optimize performance during inference tasks. This approach challenges traditional static optimization methods, allowing for fine-grained control over execution parameters at runtime, ultimately enhancing throughput and reducing latency. Through a series of controlled experiments, we will validate the effectiveness of our framework by comparing its performance against static optimization strategies on various machine learning models. Our findings will provide insights into the potential of dynamic optimizations in real-world deployment scenarios, paving the way for more efficient GPU utilization and faster inference times.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Implement a dynamic profiling tool to monitor kernel execution metrics in real-time during inference.",
      "Create a baseline using static kernel configurations and compare latency and throughput against dynamically adjusted configurations.",
      "Evaluate performance improvements across a variety of machine learning models, measuring p50/p99 latency, tokens-per-second, and energy consumption.",
      "Use A/B testing to assess the impact of dynamic adjustments on model accuracy and inference efficiency."
