Based on the literature review results, I have identified several relevant works that explore various facets of rate-distortion theory and model compression. Many of these papers provide insights into the connection between compression, generalization bounds, and the theoretical limits of model performance. Notably, the works by Sefidgaran et al. (2022) and Bu et al. (2021) emphasize the interplay between compression and generalization, which is a central theme in my proposed research.

In light of these findings, I propose a novel research idea that builds upon existing theories while introducing an unexplored angle. The proposal focuses on quantifying the trade-off between model capacity and task-specific distortion under a rate-distortion framework, specifically leveraging mutual information as a guiding principle for optimal representation learning.

### Refined Proposal

IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "mutual_information_compression_tradeoff",
    "Title": "Exploring the Mutual Information Trade-off in Model Compression and Task-specific Distortion",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Can we establish a quantifiable relationship between the mutual information of representations and the task-specific distortion in compressed models, thereby identifying optimal compression strategies that minimize distortion while preserving essential information?",
