    "Abstract": "This research proposal aims to investigate the fundamental relationship between mutual information and task-specific distortion in the context of model compression. By framing compression as a rate-distortion problem, we will develop a theoretical framework that characterizes the trade-off between the amount of information retained in a compressed model and the resulting distortion in task performance. We will employ tools from information theory to derive bounds on achievable rates and identify optimal strategies for compressing models while minimizing task-specific distortion. Empirical validation will be conducted using standard benchmarks, allowing us to quantify the effectiveness of the proposed strategies in various machine learning tasks. This work aims to bridge the gap between theoretical limits and practical implementations, providing insights into the design of efficient compression algorithms that maintain predictive sufficiency.",
