    "Abstract": "In this proposal, we investigate a novel framework for dynamic model compression that leverages information-theoretic principles to optimize compression ratios in real-time based on the task-relevance of input data. By treating model parameters as a codebook and inputs as messages, we can design a system that quantifies the mutual information between inputs and model outputs, allowing for an adaptive compression strategy that minimizes distortion. We will derive operational bounds on the bits-per-weight needed to preserve predictive sufficiency under varying data distributions. The proposed framework will involve real-time analysis of input characteristics, with dynamic adjustments in model parameters to ensure optimal compression without sacrificing performance. We will validate our approach through a series of experiments that measure the effectiveness of our dynamic compression strategy against established static methods, focusing on accuracy, efficiency, and robustness under distributional shifts.",
    "Experiments": [
