    "Related Work": "Existing literature primarily focuses on static kernel optimization strategies or heuristic approaches for kernel fusion. Works like 'Hybrid JIT-CUDA Graph Optimization' and 'Accelerating LLM Inference Throughput via Asynchronous KV Cache Prefetching' enhance performance but do not adaptively tune kernel fusion strategies at runtime. This proposal distinguishes itself by introducing a dynamic profiling-driven approach that optimally selects and fuses kernels based on measured runtime metrics, thus addressing latency-sensitive applications more effectively.",
    "Abstract": "In the realm of GPU-accelerated machine learning inference, optimizing kernel execution remains a critical challenge for achieving low-latency performance. This proposal introduces a dynamic kernel fusion tuning framework that adapts kernel fusion strategies at runtime based on continuous profiling of GPU performance metrics. By leveraging real-time data on occupancy, memory bandwidth utilization, and warp stall reasons, the framework will decide which kernels to fuse, aiming to minimize wall-clock latency while maximizing throughput. This adaptive approach contrasts with static fusion techniques, allowing for a more responsive system that can handle varying workloads and conditions. Our experiments will focus on latency-sensitive applications, employing A/B testing methodologies to assess the performance of the dynamic tuning framework against traditional static fusion methods. Expected outcomes include significant reductions in P50 and P99 latency metrics, improved tokens-per-second throughput, and valuable insights into the hardware utilization dynamics during inference.",
