  "idea": {
    "Name": "task_aware_compression_bounds",
    "Title": "Task-Aware Model Compression via Information-Theoretic Rate-Distortion Analysis",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By framing model compression as a rate-distortion problem that incorporates task-relevant mutual information, we can derive tighter bounds on achievable compression rates while maintaining predictive sufficiency.",
    "Related Work": "While existing literature has explored rate-distortion theory for model compression, few have directly integrated task-relevant mutual information and Fisher information into a unified framework. This proposal distinguishes itself by focusing on how task-aware representation compression can improve efficiency and accuracy, unlike traditional methods that often neglect these critical aspects.",
    "Abstract": "This proposal aims to investigate the intersection of model compression, information theory, and task relevance through a novel rate-distortion framework. We hypothesize that optimal compression strategies can be derived by quantifying the mutual information between model representations and the tasks they serve, utilizing Fisher information to assess sensitivity to distortion. Our approach will establish theoretical bounds on the achievable rate of compressed representations, allowing for a systematic analysis of the trade-offs between compression and task performance. We will validate these theoretical insights through a series of experiments on various neural network architectures, analyzing the performance of different compression techniques under controlled settings. Our findings will contribute to a deeper understanding of the fundamental limits of model compression, offering actionable strategies for practitioners seeking to balance efficiency and accuracy in resource-constrained environments.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Derive theoretical bounds on the mutual information and achievable rates for a variety of neural network architectures, including feedforward and recurrent layers.",
      "2. Implement a series of compression strategies (e.g., pruning, quantization) and evaluate their performance against the theoretical bounds derived.",
